:::summary
John Ronald Reuel Tolkien (1892–1973) was an English author, poet, and Oxford professor whose Catholic Christian faith and love of language and myth gave the world one of the greatest literary achievements of the 20th century: the mythology of Middle-earth, including *The Hobbit* and *The Lord of the Rings*. Tolkien believed that human storytelling — "sub-creation" — participates in the creative work of God.
:::

